This paper is likely to belong to the Robotics (cs.RO) sub-category as it deals with manipulation tasks that require robots to be in continuous contact with an object. The paper also uses a compliant tactile sensor (the TacTip) to investigate continuous tactile contact, which is a common area of research in robotics. 

The paper also involves the use of principal component analysis (PCA) for perception, which is a common technique in computer vision (cs.CV) and machine learning (cs.LG). 

Additionally, the paper discusses the generalization capabilities of the method, which is a common topic in artificial intelligence (cs.AI). 

Finally, the paper's focus on developing a more sophisticated controller for challenging manipulation or exploration tasks in unstructured environments suggests that it could also belong to the Systems and Control (cs.SY) sub-category.
